Whenever I try a new recipe from Epicurious I always glance at the reviews to see what changes other readers have suggested or how they rate it, but I rarely let a poor review stop me from trying a recipe if I like all the ingredients. That's why I'm so glad I tried this recipe, even though at this stage only 78% would make it again. We loved it, along with the peppers and onions we grilled along with it. Served with a left-over potato salad, we thought it was a great, good-for-us, meal.

Rating: 4
It's actually good contrary to some of the reviews posted here. Be sure to marinade the chicken for a longer time. That's the trick to this recipe. I also added garlic, Worcestershire sauce and chili powder to the marinade for extra kick. Rubbing salt and pepper on the chicken just before you put them into the marinade is better than sprinkling them with S&P before grilling them. And if you want it to be sweeter, add another or two tablespoons of honey. If you can't grill for any reason, you could try frying them.

Rating: 4
this was soooo good! the sauce is simple, yet so tasty. I agree. Letting it marinade for longer and making more of the sauce is the trick.

Rating: 4
We LOVE this recipe - I have made it several times, and it's always really popular. That plus how easy it is makes it a winner. A few small changes I make: Boneless chicken thighs instead of breasts are a MUST - much richer flavor. Marinate in the entire lemon mixture. Pour off however much you want to have for sauce when finished marinating, reduce per recipe. I've recently added chopped fresh rosemary, which was really good. Have never added garlic (thighs have enough flavor without it), but sounds like a good variation. During non-grill season, brown the meat, cook the onions, then braise in the marinate - different, but also really good.

